{"id": 231963322, "title": "Who Are The Six Bihar Leaders Set to Take Oath as Cabinet Ministers in Modi 3.0?", "text": "The six Bihar leaders set to take oath as cabinet ministers in Modi 3.0 include Rajiv Ranjan Singh, Ram Nath Thakur, Giriraj Singh, Chirag Paswan, Nityanand Rai, and Jitan Ram Manjhi. Discover their political journeys and roles.Rajiv Ranjan Singh alias Lalan SinghLalan Singh, former national president of Janata Dal (United) and a senior leader of his party, is a trusted loyalist of Chief Minister Nitish Kumar and has served as a minister in the state government. He is likely to take the oath as a Union minister.Singh, 69, an upper Bhumihar caste, began his political career in 1974. He later joined the Old Janata Dal Parivar and was among the founding members of the Samata Party, led by CM Kumar and former Defence Minister George Fernandes.In his long political career, Singh, a four-time MP elected from Munger, has made his mark as a strategist, troubleshooter, and hard negotiator for the JD(U), which has remained in power in Bihar as well as at the Centre in different coalition governments. Singh has served as the water resources minister and planning development minister in the state government.Last December, Singh stepped down as the national president of JD(U) amid speculations that CM Kumar was unhappy with him for getting too close to the RJD, which was an ally of the JD(U) in the Grand Alliance government that lasted from August 2022 to January 2024. CM Kumar took over as JD(U)s national president in December 2023. Later, JD(U) realigned with the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)-led National Democratic Alliance (NDA) ahead of the 2024 Lok Sabha polls.Singh fought the 2024 Lok Sabha election as a JD(U) candidate, defeating his nearest rival Anita Devi of the Rashtriya Janata Dal by a margin of 80,870 votes. nbsp;Ram Nath ThakurAnother JD(U) leader, Ram Nath Thakur, 74, is a Rajya Sabha MP and son of former Bihar Chief Minister Karpoori Thakur. Hailing from Karpoori Gram in Bihars Samastipur district, he was a member of the Bihar Legislative Council and became the minister of sugarcane industries in RJD leader Lalu Prasads first cabinet. He served as the minister of revenue and land reforms, law, information, and public relations from November 2005 to November 2010 during Nitish Kumars cabinet. He became a Rajya Sabha MP on April 10, 2014. He is likely to take the oath as a cabinet minister in the now PM Modi-led government. nbsp; Giriraj SinghBJP leader and Union minister Giriraj Singh, 71, will take the oath as a minister for the third consecutive term. He was elected from Nawada to the 16th Lok Sabha and re-elected to the 17th Lok Sabha from Begusarai, a constituency he retained even in 2024.Giriraj has served as the minister of rural development and panchayat raj department and animal husbandry and fisheries in the Modi 2.0 cabinet. He has also formerly served as the minister of cooperative, animal husbandry, and fisheries resources development in the NDA coalition government of Bihar.In the 18th Lok Sabha polls, Giriraj defeated his nearest rival Abdesh Kumar Roy of the Communist Party of India by a margin of 81,480 votes. nbsp; Chirag PaswanAn actor turned politician, Chirag Paswan, 41, president of the Lok Janshakti Party (Ram Vilas) and a three-time Lok Sabha MP from Bihar, enters the 18th Lok Sabha with an enviable distinction of having a 100% strike rate for his relatively new political outfit, having won all the five seats it contested during the recently concluded general elections.He defeated his nearest rival Shiv Chandra Ram of the RJD by a margin of 1.70 lakh votes.Paswan, who won the Hajipur seat, carries the legacy of his father, the late Ram Vilas Paswan, a Dalit leader, eight-time Lok Sabha MP, and former Union minister.Paswan was a two-time Lok Sabha MP (2014 and 2019) from Jamui before deciding this year to contest from Hajipur, his fathers stronghold, winning the seat with a margin of 1.70 lakh votes over his nearest rival Shiv Chandra Ram of the RJD.He made his film debut in 2011 with Mile Na Mile Hum, opposite Kangana Ranaut, now a BJP MP from Mandi in Himachal Pradesh. After an unsuccessful Bollywood career, Paswan learned the political ropes from his father before taking the political plunge. He has not looked back since. nbsp;Nityanand RaiA Yadav face of BJP in Bihar, Nityanand Rai, 58, started his political career as a student leader in the Akhil Bharatiya Vidyarthi Parishad (ABVP) and later won the MLA election from Hajipur assembly seat four times.Rai, elected as MP for the third time from Ujiarpur in 2024, served as a minister of state (home) in the second Prime Minister Narendra Modi cabinet from 2019-24 and is considered close to former Union Home Minister Amit Shah.The BJP has promoted Rai as a Yadav face in Bihar to counter RJDs traditional Yadav vote base and made him the state president of the party in 2016. nbsp;Jitan Ram ManjhiHindustani Awam Morcha-Secular (HAM-S) founder and former Bihar Chief Minister, Jitan Ram Manjhi, 79, is one of the Dalit faces of the National Democratic Alliance (NDA) in Bihar.Elected to the state assembly for the first time in 1980 as a Congress MLA, Manjhi has always held a prominent position in the state government. A couple of years after entering electoral politics, he was made a minister in the Chandrashekhar Singh government in Bihar.Manjhi was sworn in as the 23rd Chief Minister in May 2014 after the incumbent Chief Minister Nitish Kumar stepped down, taking moral responsibility for his partys defeat in the Lok Sabha elections. However, he was expelled from the Janata Dal (United) JD(U) after a confrontation with Kumar.Later, Manjhi founded HAM-S and projected himself as a Dalit leader. For the first time, he was elected as a member of Lok Sabha from Gaya and has been named a minister in the Prime Minister Narendra Modi-led government.Manjhi defeated his nearest rival Kumar Sarvjeet of the Rashtriya Janata Dal (RJD) by a margin of 1.10 lakh votes.President Droupadi Murmu will administer the oath of office and secrecy to Modi and his cabinet ministers at 7:15 pm on Sunday at Rashtrapati Bhavans Forecourt.", "summary": "The six Bihar leaders set to take oath as cabinet ministers in Modi 3.0 include Rajiv Ranjan Singh, Ram Nath Thakur, Giriraj Singh, Chirag Paswan, Nityanand Rai, and Jitan Ram Manjhi. Discover their political journeys and roles.  Rajiv Ranjan", "url": "https://www.oneindia.com/india/who-are-the-six-bihar-leaders-set-to-take-oath-as-cabinet-ministers-in-modi-3-0-3847715.html", "image": "https://www.oneindia.com/img/1200x60x675/2024/06/pti06-09-2024-000136b1-1717936939.jpg", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-06-09 12:47:41", "author": "Madhuri Adnal", "authors": ["Madhuri Adnal"], "language": "en", "catgory": "politics", "source_country": "in", "sentiment": 0.092}